<subSubSection id="54B7650CFFC0203BC5BF1C30FA0D62BD" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" type="key">
<keyStep id="A7592E22FFC0203BC5BF1C30FA0C6222" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
<paragraph id="1C123687FFC0203BC5BF1C30FA0C61E8" blockId="1.[151,1437,1373,1722]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
<keyLead id="A75C95B2FFC0203BC5BF1C30FA0C61E8" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
1 Lateral edges of pronotum from middle indistinctly narrowed anteriad towards markedly protruding anterior angles. Aedeagus relatively narrow, parameres slightly exceeding apex of median lobe, as in Fig. 14 (
<bibRefCitation id="783C4B76FFC0203BC1371CD3FA8C61B6" author="Shavrin, A. V. &amp; Smetana, A." box="[1055,1308,1436,1458]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" pagination="576 - 586" refId="ref1874" refString="Shavrin, A. V. &amp; Smetana, A. (2020) Anthobiomorphus, a new genus of Anthophagini Thomson, 1859 (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Omaliinae), with descritpions of two new species from China, India and Nepal. Zootaxa, 4755 (3), 576 - 586. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4755.3.9" type="journal article" year="2020">Shavrin &amp; Smetana 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Body darkbrown to black. Body larger: 3.35–4.00 mm. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="84962A02FFC0203BC63F1CF6FCDF61CA" box="[791,847,1465,1487]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[228,1351,186,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-22@2.[222,1366,180,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Habitus (Fig. 1), left maxilla (Fig. 2) and aedeagus (Figs. 3–4) of Anthobiomorphus alesi: 1–dorsal view, 2–ventral view, 3–parameral view, 4–lateral view. Scale bars (Fig. 1: 1.0 mm, Figs. 2–4: 0.1 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480120" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6480120/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
(
<bibRefCitation id="783C4B76FFC0203BC6731CF6FBC361CB" author="Shavrin, A. V. &amp; Smetana, A." box="[859,1107,1465,1487]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" pagination="576 - 586" refId="ref1874" refString="Shavrin, A. V. &amp; Smetana, A. (2020) Anthobiomorphus, a new genus of Anthophagini Thomson, 1859 (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Omaliinae), with descritpions of two new species from China, India and Nepal. Zootaxa, 4755 (3), 576 - 586. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4755.3.9" type="journal article" year="2020">Shavrin &amp; Smetana 2020</bibRefCitation>
). 
<collectingCountry id="64BA7617FFC0203BC14B1CF6FB0C61CB" box="[1123,1180,1465,1487]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="DE69F865FFC0203BC1801CF6FB6561CB" box="[1192,1269,1465,1487]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
)...................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="DBAD4D04FFC0203BC03C1C98FA0C61E8" authorityName="Shavrin &amp; Smetana" authorityYear="2020" box="[1300,1436,1495,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Anthobiomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rougemonti">
<emphasis id="2ED9EA95FFC0203BC03C1C98FA0C61E8" box="[1300,1436,1495,1516]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">A. rougemonti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1C123687FFC0203BC5BF1CBBFA0C6222" blockId="1.[151,1437,1373,1722]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
<keyLead id="A75C95B2FFC0203BC5BF1CBBFA0C6222" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">- Lateral edges of pronotum from middle distinctly narrowed anteriad towards slightly protruding apical angles. Aedeagus wider, parameres distinctly longer. Body paler and smaller.......................................................... 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="A7592E22FFC0203BC5BF1F60FA0D62BD" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
<paragraph id="1C123687FFC0203BC5BF1F60FA0D6265" blockId="1.[151,1437,1373,1722]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
<keyLead id="A75C95B2FFC0203BC5BF1F60FA0D6265" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
2 Elytra distinctly longer than broad. Parameres with narrow apical portion, significantly exceeding apex of median lobe (
<figureCitation id="84962A02FFC0203BC07E1F60FA1F6241" box="[1366,1423,1583,1605]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[228,1351,186,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-22@2.[222,1366,180,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Habitus (Fig. 1), left maxilla (Fig. 2) and aedeagus (Figs. 3–4) of Anthobiomorphus alesi: 1–dorsal view, 2–ventral view, 3–parameral view, 4–lateral view. Scale bars (Fig. 1: 1.0 mm, Figs. 2–4: 0.1 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480120" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6480120/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Body brown. Body length: 
<quantity id="DB559B62FFC0203BC4C01F03FDD06265" box="[488,576,1612,1633]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.20 mm</quantity>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="84962A02FFC0203BC7E51F03FC966265" box="[717,774,1612,1634]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[228,1351,186,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-22@2.[222,1366,180,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Habitus (Fig. 1), left maxilla (Fig. 2) and aedeagus (Figs. 3–4) of Anthobiomorphus alesi: 1–dorsal view, 2–ventral view, 3–parameral view, 4–lateral view. Scale bars (Fig. 1: 1.0 mm, Figs. 2–4: 0.1 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480120" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6480120/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
. 
<collectingCountry id="64BA7617FFC0203BC6391F03FCDA6266" box="[785,842,1612,1634]" name="Nepal" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Nepal</collectingCountry>
...................................... 
<taxonomicName id="DBAD4D04FFC0203BC0361F03FAF66265" authority="Shavrin, 2022" authorityName="Shavrin" authorityYear="2022" box="[1310,1382,1612,1633]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Anthobiomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alesi" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis id="2ED9EA95FFC0203BC0361F03FABD6265" box="[1310,1325,1612,1633]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="2ED9EA95FFC0203BC0111F03FAF66265" box="[1337,1382,1612,1633]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">alesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="2ED9EA95FFC0203BC0441F03FA0D6265" bold="true" box="[1388,1437,1612,1633]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="35EA57EEFFC0203BC0441F03FA0D6265" box="[1388,1437,1612,1633]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1C123687FFC0203BC5BF1F25FA0D62BD" blockId="1.[151,1437,1373,1722]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
<keyLead id="A75C95B2FFC0203BC5BF1F25FA0D62BD" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
- Elytra slightly longer than broad. Parameres with wide apical portions, markedly exceeding apex of median lobe, as in Fig. 16 (
<bibRefCitation id="783C4B76FFC0203BC5C01FC8FE4E6299" author="Shavrin, A. V. &amp; Smetana, A." box="[232,478,1671,1693]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" pagination="576 - 586" refId="ref1874" refString="Shavrin, A. V. &amp; Smetana, A. (2020) Anthobiomorphus, a new genus of Anthophagini Thomson, 1859 (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Omaliinae), with descritpions of two new species from China, India and Nepal. Zootaxa, 4755 (3), 576 - 586. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4755.3.9" type="journal article" year="2020">Shavrin &amp; Smetana 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Body reddish-brown. Body length: 
<quantity id="DB559B62FFC0203BC6681FC8FC5E6298" box="[832,974,1671,1693]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" metricValueMax="3.35" metricValueMin="3.25" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" unit="mm" value="3.3" valueMax="3.35" valueMin="3.25">3.25–3.35 mm</quantity>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="84962A02FFC0203BC1711FC8FB006298" box="[1113,1168,1671,1693]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[228,1351,186,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-22@2.[222,1366,180,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Habitus (Fig. 1), left maxilla (Fig. 2) and aedeagus (Figs. 3–4) of Anthobiomorphus alesi: 1–dorsal view, 2–ventral view, 3–parameral view, 4–lateral view. Scale bars (Fig. 1: 1.0 mm, Figs. 2–4: 0.1 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6480120" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6480120/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
(
<bibRefCitation id="783C4B76FFC0203BC1B41FC8FA026299" author="Shavrin, A. V. &amp; Smetana, A." box="[1180,1426,1671,1693]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" pagination="576 - 586" refId="ref1874" refString="Shavrin, A. V. &amp; Smetana, A. (2020) Anthobiomorphus, a new genus of Anthophagini Thomson, 1859 (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Omaliinae), with descritpions of two new species from China, India and Nepal. Zootaxa, 4755 (3), 576 - 586. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4755.3.9" type="journal article" year="2020">Shavrin &amp; Smetana 2020</bibRefCitation>
). 
<collectingCountry id="64BA7617FFC0203BC5CA1FEBFE8362BE" box="[226,275,1700,1722]" name="India" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">India</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="DE69F865FFC0203BC4371FEBFE0F62BE" box="[287,415,1700,1722]" country="India" name="West Bengal" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">West Bengal</collectingRegion>
), 
